title: Lesson 2
description:
Introduction

Have you ever wondered how babies inherit traits from both their parents? The answer lies in a special kind of cell division called meiosis. In this lesson, you’ll learn how sperm cells in boys and egg cells in girls are made through meiosis. These cells are called gametes, and they carry half the genetic information needed to create a new person. When a sperm and egg join during fertilization, they form a complete set of chromosomes, starting the development of a new human being.

Meiosis doesn’t just help with reproduction, it also makes sure that each child is unique. Through processes like chromosome reduction and genetic recombination, meiosis mixes genes in different ways. This is why siblings can look different from each other even though they have the same parents. By the end of this lesson, you’ll understand how meiosis works, why it’s important, and how it helps create the amazing variety we see in people today.

Content:
Meiosis and Gamete Formation
Meiosis is Essential in Sexual Reproduction

Content Standards: 
Cells are the basic unit of life and mitosis, and meiosis are the basic forms of cell division.

Learning Competency: 
explain that genetic information is passed on to offspring from both parents by the process of meiosis and fertilization;

content_data.text: Video Introduction: Meiosis and Gamete Formation

Meiosis in Male

 

Spermatogenesis is the biological process through which sperm cells are formed in male animals. This occurs in the testes, the male reproductive organs.

 

As illustrated in the figure, A diploid germ cell first enlarges and matures. It then undergoes the first meiotic division (Meiosis I), producing two cells.  Each of these cells proceeds through the second meiotic division (Meiosis II), resulting in four haploid cells. These haploid cells transform structurally, developing tails and becoming fully functional sperm cells.

 

  • In humans, each sperm cell carries 23 chromosomes—half the number found in typical body (somatic) cells, which have 46. This makes sperm haploid (n), meaning they contain only one complete set of chromosomes.

Meiosis in Female

 

Oogenesis refers to the formation of egg cells in female animals and takes place in the ovaries.

 

 Oogenesis, summarized in the figure, a diploid cell begins meiosis and, after Meiosis I, divides its cytoplasm unevenly. One cell retains most of the cytoplasm and continues developing into the egg cell. The smaller cell, called a polar body, typically degenerates and does not participate in fertilization. This process ensures that the resulting egg has sufficient nutrients and cellular components.

 

Like sperm, the egg cell is haploid and contains 23 chromosomes, ready to fuse with a sperm cell during fertilization.

 

Egg Cell and Sperm Cell

 

A human sperm is a small, motile, equipped with a tail for movement.

A human egg is much larger, nutrient-rich, and stationary. Both cells are mature haploid gametes that are capable of fertilization

 

Meiosis is Essential in Sexual Reproduction

Sexual reproduction relies on the fusion of two gametes—one from each parent.

  • Each gamete contributes half of the genetic material needed to form a new organism.
  • The sperm (from the father) and the egg (from the mother) unite during fertilization to create a zygote with a complete set of chromosomes.

 

This genetic mixing ensures diversity in offspring

 

 

Genetic Information through Meiosis

 

  • During fertilization, 1 gamete from each parent combines to form a zygote.

 

  • Because of recombination and independent assortment in meiosis, each gamete contains a different set of DNA. This produces a unique combination of genes in the resulting zygote.

 

  • Recombination in crossing over occurs during prophase I. Homologous chromosomes – 1 inherited from each parent – pair along their lengths, gene by gene.

 

  • Breaks occur along the chromosomes, and they rejoin, trading some of their genes. The chromosomes now have genes in a unique combination.

Phases of meiosis

 

During meiosis, a single diploid cell experiences two successive rounds of cell division, yet its DNA is replicated only once. This process ultimately produces four genetically distinct haploid cells, each referred to as a gamete.

 

 

The Importance of Meiosis in Sexual Reproduction

 

Genetic Diversity 

Meiosis plays a vital role in generating genetic variation among offspring. As chromosomes are randomly assorted and separated during this process, each gamete ends up with a unique combination of genetic material.

  • This variation is key to producing offspring that are genetically distinct from their parents and siblings.
  • Such diversity enhances a population’s ability to adapt to changing environments and overcome challenges.
  • Unlike asexual reproduction, which creates identical clones, sexual reproduction—powered by meiosis—ensures individuality in every generation.

 

 

Chromosome Reduction 

Meiosis cuts the chromosome number in half, converting a diploid cell (2n) into haploid gametes (n). This reduction is essential for sexual reproduction because when two haploid cells—one from each parent—join during fertilization, they reestablish the full diploid chromosome set in the newly formed zygote.

 

Without meiosis, the chromosome number would double with each generation, which would be unsustainable..

 

Genetic Recombination 

 

Genetic recombination occurs during meiosis, allowing homologous chromosomes to swap segments of DNA. This process enhances genetic variation by forming new allele combinations, ensuring that each offspring receives a distinct set of inherited traits from their parents.

- A diploid germ cell (2n = 46 chromosomes) enlarges and matures.

- It undergoes Meiosis I → produces two haploid cells.

- Each of these undergoes Meiosis II → results in four haploid cells.

activity_data.title: Kinesthetic Learning Extension – Modeling Meiosis
materials: 46 small paper strips or beads (can be cut from scrap paper or colored pape
Label half with “M” (maternal) and half with “P” (paternal)
Number each from 1 to 23 (e.g., M1–M23 and P1–P23
process_questions: How many chromosomes did each gamete end up with?
Why is it important that gametes only have 23 chromosomes?
What would happen if gametes had 46 chromosomes instead?
activity_data.detailed_instructions:
Step 1: Setup – Diploid Parent Cell

  1. Place all 46 chromosome strips (23 maternal + 23 paternal) into the two “Parent Cell” cups.
  2. These represent the full diploid set of chromosomes (2n = 46).

Step 2: Meiosis I – Separate Homologous Chromosomes

  1. Randomly select one chromosome from each pair (e.g., either M1 or P1) and place it into one of the “Gamete” cups.
  2. Repeat until each gamete cup has 23 chromosomes.

Step 3: Meiosis II – Simulate Chromatid Separation

  1. Since each strip represents a chromosome, imagine each has two chromatids.
  2. Leave the strips as-is but explain that each gamete now contains one chromatid from each original chromosome.

Step 4: Review and Reflect

  • Each gamete cup now contains a unique mix of chromosomes.
  • Discuss how this random assortment creates genetic diversity.
